Foreground, detached, and interactive.

These three flags get combined constantly, as dash i-t, or dash d, and people memorise the combinations without knowing what each one actually does. Separate them, and they're simple.

First, dash d, for detached. Without it, docker run attaches your terminal to the container's output. The output streams to your terminal, and run blocks until the container exits; hitting control-c sends the interrupt signal to it. With dash d, the container runs in the background, and run immediately returns its I-D. The output is still captured, so you can read it later with docker logs; it's just not streamed to your terminal. Use dash d for long-lived services like web servers and databases. Skip it for one-shot commands, where you want to watch the output and have run block until it's done.

Second, dash i, for interactive. This keeps standard input open. Without it, the container's input is closed immediately, so any program that reads input sees end-of-file and exits. That's fine for n-ginx, but broken for bash. With dash i, what you type is piped into the container.

Third, dash t, which allocates a t-t-y, a pseudo-terminal. That gives you a prompt, line editing, colours, and job control, the feel of a real shell rather than a raw pipe.

The famous combinations follow directly. Dash i-t gives an interactive shell, like docker run, dash i-t, ubuntu, bash; you need both, dash i to send keystrokes and dash t for the terminal feel. Dash d on its own gives a background service. And dash d-i-t runs in the background but holds standard input and a t-t-y open, so you can attach or exec into it later. The rule of thumb: use dash i-t when a human will interact, and dash d when nothing should be attached.
